ive news away free. Well, cancel that last pronouncement (as well as his visionary belief that Apple iPads “may well be the saving of the newspaper industry” before his tablet Daily crashed and burned). There are no immutable rules in this free versus paid-for game.</p> <p>Tony Gallagher, the smart new editor at the <em>Bun</em>, is making its print form a tighter, newsier product. But does the fact that its unique user scores – around a tenth of those for Gallagher’s old outfit, the <em>Telegraph</em> – mean that the <em>Sun’s</em> fabled political clout has shrivelled? Does joining in some worldwide “conversation” bring governments to heel? Only if you think that the <em>Daily Mail’s</em> impact around Downing Street has increased exponentially because its now runs “the world’s biggest newspaper online” (as opposed to pursuing a parallel conversation keener on “ample cleavages” than a Dacre boot in some hapless bureaucrat’s ribs).</p> <p>Murdoch was inevitably right to build a wall around the <em>Wall Street Journal</em>. (Thanks for the tip, <em>FT</em>). He may at least arguably be right to maintain one at the <em>Times</em> and <em>Sunday Times</em>. (Subscriber figures, good; digital global reach, zilch – though there are weird wobbles here in the restored realm of Rebekah). But downmarket – where you’re selling on tabloid pizzazz – the scene changes. Is the <em>Mail Online</em>, for all its phenomenal growth, coining profits in an ad-blocked era of mobile headaches? Will a successful celeb-and-just-fancy-that site morph into the new <em>Daily Mirror</em>? Don’t bank on it in this age of scrapped visions, black holes and advertising upheaval. The new, free digiBun probably won’t be a staging post to some roseate red-top existence; more an ad hoc reinforcement of the print presence in yet another vision of the future that may not endure beyond the day after tomorrow.</p> <p>■ One of the snags with “native advertising” (ie paid-for advertorial cooked up in-house or designated as an “independent publication by Upper Reach”) is that 18 pages of the stuff in the centre of the <em>Times</em> isn’t infinitely flexible when Cairo business push turns to Sinai airbus shove in the course of a Cobra meeting. The grounding of UK flights to Sharm el-Sheikh, leaving up to 20,000 panic-stricken Brits “stranded” in a sybaritic holiday paradise, is page 1 news. But turn far inside into the Upper Reaches of “Welcome President Sisi” to read how “Sweeping reforms have put Egypt back on the investment map”. ; how a “Resilient economy is gaining significant traction”; how “An ever steady banking sector looks to increase penetration”. And, of course, how “Red Sea resorts lead Egypt tourism revival”. You might call the whole thing “Stranded without a native second edition”.</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10955235","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-08T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2402879","internalContentCode":"458348756","internalRevision":"111","publication":"The Observer","trailText":"Sun shows there are no hard and fast rules in free v paid-for game","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Sun’s paywall saga shows it’s never too late to change the rules","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","byline":"Peter Preston","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T09:00:03.972Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/c3e5f3c4d576b8a86855b6fb31475564a1bed6d3/175_0_3105_1863/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"563cca76e4b0fd5772b4d8bc","newspaperPageNumber":"45","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-11T09:00:02Z","standfirst":"Rupert Murdoch was right to build a wall around the Wall Street Journal and the Times. But downmarket the scene changes","linkText":"Sun’s paywall saga shows it’s never too late to change the rules","showInRelatedContent":"false","lastModified":"2015-11-08T09:00:03.992Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/nov/08/sun-newspaper