ws/uknews","sectionName":"From the Observer"}]},{"id":"commentisfree/2015/nov/08/abortion-law-mps-commons-devolve-scotland","type":"article","sectionId":"commentisfree","webTitle":"This threat to abortion law must be fought by MPs of all hues | Yvette Cooper","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T00:08:01Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"714","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4e2e7","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/c87730d42844956322185ae500dd3c6910464b16/0_134_3500_2101/140.jpg","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"c87730d42844956322185ae500dd3c6910464b16\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/c87730d42844956322185ae500dd3c6910464b16/0_134_3500_2101/1000.jpg\" alt=\"The anti-abortion protest group Bound 4 Life demonstrates at the US Supreme Court last month.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The anti-abortion protest group Bound 4 Life demonstrates at the US Supreme Court last month.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Jonathan Ernst/Reuters</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>Campaigners against abortion in Britain are getting louder. On Monday, I fear parliament will play into their hands and vote to make it harder to defend a sensible framework of abortion law that gives women the healthcare they need.</p> <p>Nearly 50 years ago, the Abortion Act put an end to backstreet abortions – an end to the terrible deaths of desperate women and to the imprisonment of doctors who tried to help them, perhaps carrying out abortions for victims of abuse or rape or for women with serious health problems.</p> <p>Since then, there have been repeated attempts to change the law. Some people oppose abortion on principle – perhaps on faith grounds – and I respect those views, although I disagree with them. But each time, after serious debate, parliament has chosen to support the current framework, which set limits but treats abortion as a healthcare issue to be decided by women with their doctor.</p> <p>Without proper consultation or debate, parliament will vote on whether to break up that framework and devolve abortion law to the Scottish parliament. To do this without the serious consultation that the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/nov/27/scottish-devolution-smith-commission-key-points\" title=\"\">Smith commission</a> recommended is unwise. It could open the door to a new round of intensive, targeted pressure for restrictions both north and south of the border, and the fragmentation of important healthcare rights, which won’t be good for women in Scotland or England and Wales.</p> <p>The SNP government says women shouldn’t worry, because they have no plans to change the abortion law. I’m sure they don’t. But that’s not how it works. This amendment to devolve abortion to Scotland wasn’t put forward initially by the SNP or Conservative government – it was proposed by a small group of backbench MPs who publicly oppose abortion. And there’s a reason they did so.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>Many American women now have to travel hundreds of miles to get a safe, legal abortion</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>Look what’s happened in the US. Anti-abortion campaigners, after failing for 40 years at federal level to overturn the Roe v Wade judgment on legal abortions, decided to target individual states one at a time instead. Their lobbying has been intense and targeted and many states have given in – more than 200 anti-abortion measures have been enacted across 30 states in the past three years. Many American women now have to travel hundreds of miles to get a safe, legal abortion.</p> <p>If abortion law is devolved to Scotland, it would be naive to think that anti-abortion campaigners won’t try to change the law or to test the commitment of the Scottish parliament over its new jurisdiction. That’s why they called for abortion to be devolved. At most, it will mean a new bout of lobbying that makes women feel uncomfortable about their choices and puts medical professionals under pressure. At the very least, it means different laws north and south of the border.</p> <p>Already, for historical reasons, we have a different framework for Northern Ireland – and each year hundreds of women travel across the sea for an abortion as a result. I don’t think we should fragment the system further and make more women travel when it would be better for them to make a personal decision with proper advice at home.</p> <p>Nor can we take for granted that aggressive, pressurising tactics of US campaign groups won’t ever be imported here. Already there are concerns that US-based groups such as <a href=\"https://40daysforlife.com/\" title=\"\">40 Days of Life</a> and <a href=\"http://abort67.co.uk/\" title=\"\">Abort67</a> have started to sponsor clinic protests here; I’ve heard appalling stories from patients and staff who have been abused, harassed, intimidated or filmed walking through the clinic door.</p> <p>Abortion politics is always sensitive. And there will always democratic debate about whether the framework is right. But let’s not be pressured into rapid changes without thinking through the consequences. At a minimum, MPs should follow the Smith commission and delay until there has been proper consultation with women and health professionals.</p> <p>For those of us who believe the current laws in England, Scotland and Wales are broadly right, surely we are stronger if we stand together to defend them against those who want to turn back the clock, rather than leaving each other to face the heat of the campaign alone.</p> <p><em>Yvette Cooper is Labour MP for Normanton, Pontefract, Castleford &amp; Knottingley</em></p>","internalOctopusCode":"10958994","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-08T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2403169","int