ne-Anne Gadhia.</p> <p>The boss of Virgin Money, asked by the chancellor what could be done about the fact that fewer women get to the top in banking, fund management and insurance than in any other sector, was there to set out her bold views on gender balance.</p> <p>At the Downing Street soiree, Gadhia said companies should set their own gender-balance record, put senior individuals in charge of attaining the goals, and include the targets among those used to set bonuses.</p> <p>“In the City we are successful in delivering targets. Let’s think about how that delivery has worked successfully in financial returns, customer satisfaction, environmental policy and see if we can apply it to gender progress and diversity,” Gadhia said after the reception. “This is about women from the very beginning of their careers… This is about creating an environment where all women can become senior if that is want they want to do. I’m trying to have a level playing field for everybody.”</p> <p>The reasons she lists for the imbalance are well-known: motherhood, remuneration, the old boys’ network. But she deliberately avoided suggesting an industry-wide target, such as the one set by Lord (Mervyn) Davies to encourage firms to get more women in boardrooms. “Quotas and imposed targets could have all sorts of backlash,” she said. “We don’t say to organisations ‘you have to have a customer satisfaction score of x’.” Requiring companies to publish their goals should be the way to hold them to account, she suggested. She did not believe any job in financial services should be out of the reach of women.</p> <p>Much could be done to break down stereotypes. Advisers on mergers and acquisitions, for instance – a line of business notorious for long hours of negotiations – could change working practices. One idea would be for advisers to work round the clock on one deal for three months and take a break before starting on the next one. “If we can just get that sort of thought going,” she said.</p> <p>What about her own working hours? Gadhia said she didn’t keep track.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"50ae2e939b0aefce3d373a8b282eab0bd8ffc14c\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/50ae2e939b0aefce3d373a8b282eab0bd8ffc14c/0_59_4512_2709/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Gadhia during a panel discussion on women in finance at No 11 Downing Street last week.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Gadhia during a panel discussion on women in finance at No 11 Downing Street last week.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Chris Radburn/PA</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>“I live one life. When people ask me how many hours I work, I don’t really know. Given the technology [available] today, I work all the time but I don’t feel absent from home. Do I have a work-life balance? I have a life that feels balanced and full and I don’t think any part of it feels underinvested-in.”</p> <p>Gadhia said she encourages women to take the maximum amount of maternity leave time that they can. She took only six weeks, which in retrospect was “stupid”. “I worry that because we want to make it the norm for women to work that it feels wrong to stay at home. It’s about giving men and women choices.”</p> <p>More thought also needs to be given to the transition back into work, she says, though she “never had that dislocation in coming back” from maternity leave. Her husband Ashok, whose surname she uses, gave up his job when they had their daughter Amy after 19 years of marriage and six courses of IVF. He was also at Downing Street to support her efforts to promote gender balance.</p> <p>At the event, City women were lining up and taking selfies of themselves in No 11; Gadhia appeared as starstruck as anyone. That would surprise many. Once an outsider – not just as a women but as the boss of a so-called challenger bank – Gadhia has become part of the establishment. At the Mansion House dinner in June she sat next to Osborne as he outlined his settlement with the City after five years of banker-bashing.</p> <p>She has had her setbacks. She failed in her first attempt to buy Northern Rock when it was on the brink of collapse in 2008. She had a second try and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2011/nov/17/northern-rock-virgin-money-taxpayer\" title=\"\">won control of the sound part of the nationalised lender</a> three years later for Virgin Money, backed by Sir Richard Branson, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/nov/13/virgin-money-float-85m-richard-branson\" title=\"\">which has since floated on the stock market</a>. She sold around a quarter of her stake for £2m.</p> <p>She went to Virgin after leaving RBS (where her problem was not with Fred Goodwin - now stripped of his knighthood - but others) before the 2008 crash. Referring back to a previous giant financial scandal, Gadhia recalls feeling at the time “this is going to be the next Enron.”</p> <p>A better gender balance might at least have helped in 2008, she feels.</p> <p>“If there had been more gender balance and diversity pre-crisis we would still have had a crisis, but I bet you it would have been less rocky, less bumpy and less painful.”</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10954679","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-08T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2402993","internalContentCode":"458349865","internalRevision":"115","publication":"The Observer","trailText":"Virgin Money boss Jayne-Anne Gadhia wants more women to rise to the top in finance and made headlines with her call for bonuses to be pegged to firms’ gender-balance record","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Virgin chief on the money for battle over gender pay gap","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","byline":"Jill Treanor","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-07T16:00:09.104Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/b9534e96dc5a510b0575acbaa0f13f60e70a3efd/