e":"Stand by for the next generation of financial advice … from a robot","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T07:00:01Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"1300","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4exz3","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/e5f7be34650d3b24d21a33acd95cdf61e956cb76/0_354_5293_3175/140.jpg","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"e5f7be34650d3b24d21a33acd95cdf61e956cb76\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/e5f7be34650d3b24d21a33acd95cdf61e956cb76/0_354_5293_3175/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Tom and Lucy Watkins decided to use Nutmeg, an online investment company, for ‘convenience, and what seemed reasonable fees’. \" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Tom and Lucy Watkins decided to use Nutmeg, an online investment company, for ‘convenience, and what seemed reasonable fees’. </span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Karen Gray Photography</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>A robot revolution could transform the way you manage your money within the next few decades – from instantly tailoring an investment portfolio to suit your circumstances, to sorting your tax affairs, debts and financial planning on your mobile device over breakfast.</p> <p>According to a report last week from analysts at the Bank of America Merrill Lynch, artificial intelligence is set to take over a variety of jobs within 20 years, including financial advice.</p> <p>This new breed of so-called “robo-advisers” will not offer you a personal chat, complete with tea and biscuits. However, you also won’t pay through the nose for the service, enabling more people to afford the advice they desperately need.</p> <p>A consultation into how this type of financial advice could work more effectively for consumers was launched jointly by the Treasury and the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) last month. It includes a review of the role robo-advice could play in solving problems around accessing advice, with traditional providers often unable to cater for anyone apart from the very wealthy.</p> <p>Robo-advisers have been around for a while in the US. A report from Cerulli Associates last week said that robo-advice platforms are expected to reach $489bn (£323bn) in assets under management by 2020, up from $18.7bn today.</p> <p>Services are increasingly being launched in the UK too, targeting investors who need help with simple investment choices, but who can’t afford the often steep costs of face-to-face advice, which can swiftly amount to thousands of pounds. </p> <p>But if you’re expecting to be faced with a friendly machine such as C-3PO, prepare to be disappointed. Current robo-advisers are essentially online wealth management services which use algorithms to suggest automated investment portfolios based on customers’ goals and attitude to risk. Services in the UK include <a href=\"http://www.fiveraday.co.uk/\" title=\"\">Fiver a Day</a>, <a href=\"https://www.moneyontoast.com/\" title=\"\">Money on Toast</a> and <a href=\"http://www.wealthhorizon.com/\" title=\"\">Wealth Horizon</a>.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2012/dec/14/end-of-line-for-commission\">End of the line for commission</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Ian McKenna, director at the <a href=\"http://www.ftrc.co/\" title=\"\">Finance &amp; Technology Research Centre</a>, says: “Many digital services are currently very much in their infancy, and the organisations offering them make it very clear that they are not a substitute for holistic financial planning. Using one of today’s digital advisers is a bit like going to the pharmacy and asking them for advice rather than going to see your GP.</p> <p>“Over time, this type of service is likely to become increasingly sophisticated. It should help democratise advice so that everyone who needs it can get it, and it isn’t unaffordable to the masses.”</p> <p>McKenna admits he dislikes the term robo-advice, while others claim it is likely to mislead consumers.</p> <p>Gina Miller, founder of online investment manager <a href=\"http://scmdirect.com/\" title=\"\">SCM Direct</a>, says: “It is often unclear where the boundaries lie between a personal recommendation and information/execution-only, and whether this is transparent enough for customers. I am astonished that more traditional advisers have not been up in arms about this.”</p> <p>Many online investment services are keen to distance themselves from the “robo-adviser” tag. Jason Hollands of online investment service <a href=\"http://www.tilneybestinvest.co.uk/\" title=\"\">Tilney Bestinvest</a> says: “‘Robo-advice’ has become a bit of a faddish term, and it isn’t how we would choose to describe our ready-made portfolios, as we’re not providing advice but a simple, step-by-step process to help investors select a managed portfolio without the need for an advised process.”</p> <p>Online investment manager <a href=\"http://www.nutmeg.com/\" title=\"\">Nutmeg</a>, which matches investors to portfolios depending on their goals and for how long and how much they want to invest, claims that what sets it apart from US robos is its active asset allocation approach.</p> <p>Its chief executive, Nick Hungerford, says: “You need to be strategic in how you take asset allocation decisions; it can’t just be ‘the computer says’.” The site charges an annual fee ranging from 0.3% up to 1% depending on how much you invest.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>He was very honest but said because we had less than £100,000 it really wasn't worth either his time or ours</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>Lucy Watkins, 34, who is self-employed and works for the civil service, and her husband Tom, 35, a solicitor, invest £500 a month into a medium to high risk Isa portfolio through Nutmeg. Tom has also transferred his pension to Nutmeg.</p> <p>One of Tom’s work colleagues had recommended a financial adviser, but the couple were told that they didn’t have sufficient savings to proceed. Tom says: “I had a very interesting meeting with him and he worked hard, but he was very honest and said because we had less than £100,000 it wasn’t really worth either his time or ours for me to move my pension pot to them.</p> <p>“In the end we went with convenience and what seemed like reasonable fees. Nutmeg made it all very straightforward and their openness made me trust them. I was, however, nervous about their lack of track record. I am a bit worried by the fact that my pension pot has dropped fairly considerably since I’ve moved it to them, but I hope that’s reflective of the market as a whole.”</p> <h2><strong>Is robo</strong>-advice right for you?</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"889ebf68bce534acfe0dbc3fc56bb2d0f58e40c3\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/11/6/1446814653903/2fef7ed1-c7b3-4bbd-b73a-29d05cd9dcac-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"If your affairs are simple, a robo-adviser is a low-cost option.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">If your affairs are simple, a robo-adviser is a low-cost option.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Kacper Pempel/Reuters</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>If your financial affairs are simple and you are just looking for help on where, for example, to invest your Isa allowance, then a robo-adviser is a low-cost option.</p> <p>However, this type of service is not suitable for anyone with complex financial affairs who needs help with things such as trusts, estate planning or complicated retirement decisions.  </p> <p>Justin Modray of <a href=\"https://www.candidfinancialadvice.com/\" title=\"\">Candid Financial Advice</a> says: “These services focus their advice, or guidance, on deciding which of their investment portfolios suits the amount of risk you are comfortable taking. Don’t expect financial advice covering areas such as tax planning or reviewing existing investments and pensions.</p> <p>“That is not to say that such services aren’t worthwhile: the task of choosing and monitoring investments is at least taken off your hands. But if you are considering issues such as whether to transfer a pension, then robo-advisers currently fall short.”</p> <p>If you prefer face-to-face advice, you can find an independent financial adviser in your area through the financial advice trade body <a href=\"https://www.unbiased.co.uk/\" title=\"\">unbiased.co.uk</a>, or through the website <a href=\"http://vouchedfor.co.uk\" title=\"\">vouchedfor.co.uk</a>. Alternatively, you can find an adviser through the <a href=\"http://thepfs.org/yourmoney\" title=\"\">Personal Finance Society</a>.</p> <h2>Online investment advice in the UK</h2> <p>■ <a href=\"https://www.moneyontoast.com/\" title=\"\"><strong>Money on Toast</strong></a><br /><strong>How it works:</strong> You complete an online questionnaire which takes around four minutes, and the site will then send you a “suitability report” by email. This contains information and product recommendations, as well as links to any recommended fund documents. A telephone helpline is available.</p> <p><strong>What you pay:</strong> There is a 1% annual management charge, plus underlying fund charges of 0.49%.</p> <p>■ <a href=\"http://www.wealthhorizon.com/\" title=\"\"><strong>Wealth Horizon</strong></a><br /><strong>How it works:</strong> You answer a series of simple questions about your finances and attitudes towards money online. The site will then determine a portfolio of investments designed to provide a return that is in line with your attitude to risk. A telephone helpline is available.</p> <p><strong>What you pay:</strong> There’s an initial investment charge of 0.25%, ongoing investment charges of 0.75% and underlying fund charges of 0.18%.</p> <p>■<strong> </strong><a href=\"http://www.fiveraday.co.uk/\" title=\"\"><strong>Fiver A Day</strong></a><br /><strong>How it works:</strong> You are asked questions about how much you want to invest and over what sort of timeframe and level of risk. The site then recommends how your money should be invested and shows projections for how it could perform. The process takes about 10 minutes.</p> <p><strong>What you pay:</strong> You’ll be charged 0.25% of each initial contribution. There are ongoing charges of 0.34% a year for managing your investments.</p> <p>■<strong> </strong><a href=\"http://www.eqinvestors.co.uk/simplyeq/\" title=\"\"><strong>Simply EQ</strong></a><br /><strong>How it works: </strong>You select one of three investment approaches (passive, active or ethical). The site then builds an appropriate risk-rated portfolio. Advisers are available over the phone.</p> <p><strong>What you pay:</strong> Charges are tiered, but range from 0.39% up to 1.19%. There are also fund charges ranging from 0.18% up to 0.95% depending on the portfolio.</p> <p><em>* All sites offer regulated automated advice</em></p>","internalOctopusCode":"10950333","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-08T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2402706","internalContentCode":"458347219","internalRevision":"94","publication":"The Observer","trailText":"The Treasury and the Financial Conduct Authority are assessing the benefits of an automated service which could provide help for smaller investors","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Stand by for the next generation of financial advice … from a robot","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","byline":"Melanie Wright","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T07:00:01Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/e5f7be34650d3b24d21a33acd95cdf61e956cb76/0_354_5293_3175/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"563c9f1fe4b0bbf4cf2cd170","newspaperPageNumber":"46"