nt":"856","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4e2e2","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/0270444c014c498bbd2872e361989b4efbcc453e/0_0_2384_1430/140.jpg","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"0270444c014c498bbd2872e361989b4efbcc453e\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/0270444c014c498bbd2872e361989b4efbcc453e/0_0_2384_1430/1000.jpg\" alt=\"TS Eliot\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">TS Eliot in the studio in 1941.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Rex Features</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>In a letter to his brother in 1922, TS Eliot once enigmatically wrote that he hoped to solve his “problem of living a double or triple life”. Now, 50 <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/jan/10/from-tom-to-ts-eliot-world-poet\" title=\"to Guardian anniv appraisal\">years after his death</a>, an amateur British scholar is creating waves in the growing academic world of Eliot studies because he believes he has unravelled a long-running literary riddle that shows what Eliot meant: the poet was playing a drawn-out game with names that split his identity in three.</p> <p>The poet’s fondness for crosswords, for Scrabble and for the puns he used in letters to his friend Groucho Marx offered the first clue. An ardent Eliot fan from Glasgow, David Liston, 59, began to look for wordplay and now thinks the answer has been there for all to see <a href=\"http://thewasteland.touchpress.com\" title=\"link to app site\">in the poem <em>The Waste Land</em></a>, perhaps the greatest English-language work of the 20th century. Eliot experts have long wondered about the name of one of the poem’s many fleeting characters. At one point an English bank clerk called Stetson appears, and his ostensibly American name has often leaped out at readers:</p> <p><em>There I saw one I knew, and stopped him, crying: “Stetson!</em></p> <p><em>You who were with me in the ships at Mylae!”</em></p> <p>Rival theories have often suggested that Stetson might stand for Eliot himself, since he worked for Lloyds bank and was born in America. But the choice of such an unusual name has been variously linked to the Stetson hat maker (by Allen Ginsberg, among others); to feminist lecturer Charlotte Perkins Stetson; to an American banker (by Eliot’s wife, Valerie); and to a place in St Louis,<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/feb/11/young-eliot-st-louis-waste-land-robert-crawford-review\" title=\"review of biography\"> the poet’s birthplace</a>. More oddly, a link has been made to the hat worn by the Anzacs at Gallipoli. It was also thought to be a possible alternate identity for his friend and fellow poet, Ezra Pound.</p> <p>A demanding read, although written in popular slang in sections, <em>The Waste Land</em>’s verses, published in 1922, have been subjected to more close academic study than any other modern poem. Yet Liston, who previously worked in publishing, came across an anagram.</p> <p>Bearing in mind Eliot’s penchant for three-part names, including the hero of his well-known earlier work The Love Song of J Alfred Prufrock, and the feline stars of his <em>Old Possum’s Book of Practical Cats</em>, each said to have three names, Liston took the poet’s own name, Thomas Stearns Eliot, and spotted something: if you take out “Thomas”, and then transpose the letters of “Stearns Eliot”, you get “Ariel Stetson”, the names of the poetic force and the bank official in the poem.</p> <p>The Burial of the Dead section of the <em>The Waste Land</em> had originally started with a stanza about “Tom” (“First we had a couple of feelers down at Tom’s place, There was old Tom, boiled to the eyes, blind”), and the poem is recognised to contain many allusions to Shakespeare’s Ariel, the ethereal figure from <em>The Tempest</em> who is repeatedly associated with the poetic muse, including by Percy Bysshe Shelley and Sylvia Plath. Part of Ariel’s line, “Those are pearls that were his eyes” appears in <em>The Waste Land,</em> even though Pound tried to edit them out.</p> <p>Encouraged by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/jan/29/poetry.oxforduniversity\" title=\"link to guardian\">respected academic Christopher Ricks</a>, who has recently updated his own theories about the poem, Liston put forward his idea to the TS Eliot Society, which has published it.</p> <p>Liston admits Eliot’s joke isn’t a great one: “‘Thomas Ariel Stetson’ would not have won many prizes as an anagram, but Eliot was not out to collect prizes,” he said. However, it does work as a hidden code, Liston believes, because the poet’s public only knew him as TS Eliot.</p> <p>However, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/craig-raine\" title=\"link to Guardian page on poet\">the award-winning poet and Eliot expert, Craig Raine</a>, is among those who are not convinced. He thinks the Stetson line about the ships at Mylae, a 260BC battle during the first Punic war, is there to point up the strong suggestion of previous lives lived that runs throughout <em>The Waste Land</em>.</p> <p>“The line means exactly what it says. It’s one of the most important lines in the poem, with huge implications,” said Raine, who spoke on this subject at the TS Eliot summer school this year. For him, Stetson stands clearly for 19th and 20th-century America. “The only thing that might make the statement possible would be that Stetson had a previous life and that the [narrative] speaker of <em>The Waste Land</em> had a previous life, too.”</p> <p>Liston argues that there is a theme or “hidden agenda” behind the anagram. It was an emblem of Eliot’s divided self, both as a poet and a person. Dubbed the “poet of impersonality”, Eliot is often quoted as suggesting poetry was “not the expression of personality, but an escape from personality” in his 1919 essay, <em>Tradition and the Individual Talent</em>.</p> <p>More support for the anagram theory comes from Eliot himself. “It’s interesting to cut yourself to pieces once in a while, and wait to see if the fragments will sprout,” he once wrote.</p> <p>In his 1933 Harvard lecture, the poet also said, “there may be personal causes which make it impossible for a poet to express himself in any but an obscure way.”</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10958619","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-08T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2403164","internalContentCode":"458351512","internalRevision":"89","publication":"The Observer","trailText":"Hidden anagram points to the poet himself as the bank clerk hailed in a London crowd, claims amateur fan","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Who is the mysterious ‘Stetson’ in TS Eliot’s Waste Land? One scholar has a clue…","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","byline":"Vanessa Thorpe","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T00:05:02.309Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/0270444c014c498bbd2872e361989b4efbcc453e/0_0_2384_1430/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"563dd3ede4b0ace666f8b91c","newspaperPageNumber":"7","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-15T00:05:00+00:00","standfirst":"<p>Hidden anagram points to the poet himself as the bank clerk hailed in a London crowd, claims amateur fan</p>","linkText":"Who is the mysterious ‘Stetson’ in TS Eliot’s Waste Land? One scholar has a clue…","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-08T00:05:02.426Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/08/ts-eliot-waste-land-stetson-anagram-riddle","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2015/nov/08/ts-eliot-waste-land-stetson-anagram-riddle","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"0270444c014c498bbd2872e361989b4efbcc453e","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/0270444c014c498bbd2872e361989b4efbcc453e/0_0_2384_1430/2000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"THIS COPYR