rding the Sinai air crash appeared to be a mixture of scepticism, caution and an implacable hostility towards Islamic State.</p> <p>Above all, many Russians seemed hesitant to draw any conclusions about the causes of disaster, or to tie it to Moscow’s airstrikes in Syria.</p> <p>“You want me to say it was a bad idea to bomb Syria? Personally I think it was high time we destroy Isis,” said one woman who gave her name as Tatiana Vladimirovna. She said she had worked in the aviation industry and thought negligence probably caused the crash.</p> <p>“Isis is horrible, they’re worse than Hitler,” said Natalya Petrovna. They’re destroying people, they’re destroying their history. Have you watched TV? They’re now engaged in recruiting our girls.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/06/mounting-suspicions-sinai-plane-crash-russian-response\">Mounting suspicions over Sinai plane crash force Russian response</a> </p> </aside>  <p>“Do you think comrade Putin will let them take down our planes just like that?” she said, when asked about the possibility of terrorist attacks in revenge for Russia’s campaign in Syria. “Our military looks pretty good now compared to others.”</p> <p>Vladimir, who did not want to give his surname, said Russians’ support for the Syria campaign would remain unaffected even if a bomb was shown to have brought down the plane. </p> <p>“A plane crashed, so what? Our planes have crashed before because the pilot was drunk,” he said.</p> <p>“Whether [perceptions] change will depend on our zombie-box,” he added, using a term for state TV popular among the opposition.</p> <p>On Saturday the Russian newspaper <em>Kommersant</em> quoted a source saying Egyptian forensic scientists had determined that several passengers died from “bomb blast trauma”.</p> <p>But, in general, Russian media remain hesitant to raise the spectre of a terrorist attack. State news agency RIA Novosti quoted an unnamed Russian official in the crash investigation as saying: “At the moment it is only possible to talk about the presence of undefined sounds registered by the flight recorder,” and that it was “premature” to say they came from an explosion.</p> <p>The official government newspaper, <em>Rossiyskaya Gazeta</em>, said the decoding of the black box did not provide conclusive data that an explosive device had been on board.</p>       <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2015/nov/07/russian-tourists-await-flights-at-sharm-el-sheikh-airport-video\"            data-short-url=\"http://gu.com/p/4e2fd\"                    data-show-ads=\"true\"            data-video-id=\"2403202\"            data-video-name=\"Russian tourists await flights at Sharm el-Sheikh airport – video\"            data-video-provider=\"guardian.co.uk\"            > <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-563dfb1ee4b09da63347fd33\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2015/11/07/151107Russian_desk.mp4\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/HLS/2015/11/07/151107Russian.m3u8\"/><source src=\"http://multimedia.guardianapis.com/interactivevideos/video.php?octopusid=10930696&amp;format=video/webm\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2015/11/07/151107Russian_large.3gp\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2015/11/07/151107Russian_small.3gp\"/> </video> <figcaption>Russian tourists at Sharm el-Sheikh airport.</figcaption> </figure>   <p>In the days since the crash, Russian state media have largely avoided discussing the possibility of a bomb, instead focusing on the official line that any speculation before the end of the investigation is harmful.</p> <p>The British decision on Thursday to suspend flights to Egypt and David Cameron’s statement that an explosive device was “more likely than not” the cause of the crash have been met with scepticism and hostility by officials and media in Russia. </p> <p>One senator said the statement had been intended to put “psychological pressure” on Russia over its Syria operations.</p> <p>Even after Putin stopped Russian flights to Egypt over safety concerns on Friday, his spokesman, Dmitry Peskov, insisted that this “does not mean that a terrorist attack is the main suspected cause of the catastrophe”. </p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/07/russia-condemns-charlie-hebdo-for-sinai-plane-crash-cartoons\">Russia condemns Charlie Hebdo for Sinai plane crash cartoons</a> </p> </aside>  <p>State-owned broadcaster Channel One quoted him as saying: “There are no clear indications in favour of this explanation.”</p> <p>The Russian tour operators’ association said on Saturday that 93 planes would be dispatched to Egypt this weekend to begin bringing back the 80,000 Russians now stranded there.</p> <p>Islamist groups have called for attacks on Russia since Putin began airstrikes at the end of September. State TV, which remains the main source of news for most Russians, has framed the campaign as one against Isis; Putin has declared that Russia must destroy terrorists in Syria rather than “wait until they come to our home”.</p> <p>Polling has shown that while Russians largely approve of the airstrikes, most do not favour boots on the ground, and memories of the Soviet Union’s disastrous war in Afghanistan linger. </p> <p>Lev Gudkov, director of the independent pollster Levada Centre, said earlier this month that most hope the operation will be quick and bloodless.</p> <p>A terrorist attack against Russia could generate resentment towards the Kremlin for having become involved in the conflict, he said, but would also probably inspire many to rally around the flag in the face of a terrorist threat.</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10959711","productionOffice":