/focus","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theobserver/news/focus","sectionName":"From the Observer"}]},{"id":"news/2015/nov/08/big-issue-medical-research","type":"article","sectionId":"news","webTitle":"How to make sure that the medicine goes down well | big issue","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T00:06:01Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"595","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4exn8","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/a0e8f2fea3ab406511d39f45fc2880b7bd73d17b/0_289_5616_3371/140.jpg","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"a0e8f2fea3ab406511d39f45fc2880b7bd73d17b\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/a0e8f2fea3ab406511d39f45fc2880b7bd73d17b/0_289_5616_3371/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Aseem Malhotra says we are being prescribed too many medicines.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Aseem Malhotra says we are being prescribed too many medicines.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: eye35.pix/Alamy</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>We would like to reassure Dr Aseem Malhotra that the Academy of Medical Sciences is taking great care to ensure independence and inclusivity in our inquiry into how society judges the safety of medicines (“<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/01/drugs-pharma-doctors-patients\" title=\"\">How too much medicine can kill you</a>”, Comment).</p> <p>The project will explore three crucial issues that have an impact on society’s interpretation of evidence: the methods used to collect and evaluate evidence, possible conflicts of interest arising in the process of evidence gathering and evaluation, and the process of communicating evidence within the profession and to the public.</p> <p>A programme of public and patient engagement will take place throughout the project to ensure discussions are informed by the views of the wider society. In the interest of transparency, the names of those involved in the three work streams and their potential conflicts of interest will be published on our website</p> <p>To further address Dr Malhotra’s concerns, the academy supports the principles of transparency of research at the core of the AllTrials petition. While we cannot sign up to campaigns on behalf of our fellowship, we have encouraged our fellows to do so in a personal capacity since the campaign launched.</p> <p>Our support for transparency on clinical trials and AllTrials has been available on our website since 2013. </p> <p><strong>Sir John Tooke PMedSci</strong></p> <p>President, </p> <p>Academy of Medical Sciences</p> <p>London W1</p> <p>Dr Malhotra’s article highlights the modern phenomenon of “scepticaemia”. It is becoming increasingly popular to criticise primary research, reviewed retrospectively many years after its original publication with no reference to the original authors. Science is empirical and leads to gradual change. Malhotra talks of over-medicalisation; however, statins have undoubtedly saved more lives than they have harmed.</p> <p>Instead of the current preoccupation with pulling apart research done with the best intentions, perhaps the exponents of this phenomenon would do well to help improve research methodology rather than simply criticise it. I fear that even initiatives such as AllTrials will, through academic zealotry, lead to a climate of fear in science that will suppress legitimate research.</p> <p><strong>Andrew Beggs</strong></p> <p>Wellcome Trust clinician scientist fellow</p> <p>Institute of Cancer &amp; Genomic Medicine</p> <p>University of Birmingham</p> <p>Many older people are taking hundreds of pills a week and the article raises a hugely important issue concerning how we review and manage older people’s medicines. Recent research, published last week in Dispensing Health in Later Life, reveals that GPs are very concerned that their older patients are taking too many medicines and not taking them as prescribed.</p> <p>While Dr Malhotra outlines the responsibilities he believes lie with the pharmaceutical industry and policy makers, we believe there is a solution much closer to home. High street pharmacists can play a huge role in addressing this issue.</p> <p>Regular medicine use reviews, undertaken by high street pharmacists, would help older people take medicines correctly and understand potential side-effects. To achieve this, GPs and pharmacists must work closely together and pharmacists should be given access to basic health records, with the patient’s consent. Some 18.7 prescriptions are dispensed per person per year at a cost of £8.9bn, but ensuring correct use of medicines can help people take fewer medicines.</p> <p><strong>Professor Rob Darracott </strong>chief executive, Pharmacy Voice; <strong>Dr Nav Chana </strong>chairman, National Association of Primary Care;<strong> Janet Morrison </strong>chief executive, Independent Age;<strong> Rick Stern </strong>director, Primary Care Foundation;<strong> Dr Michael Dixon </strong>chairman, NHS Alliance; <strong>Professor Martin Green, </strong>chief executive, Care England</p> <p>Dr Malhorta writes that “it’s time to restrain the harms of too much medicine”. There is a saying in Buddhism: don’t just do something; sit there.</p> <p><strong>Professor Brendan Kelly</strong></p> <p>Department of Psychiatry</p> <p>University College Dublin</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10954353","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-08T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2402684","internalContentCode":"458347122","internalRevision":"59","publication":"The Observer","trailText":"Transparency of research is essential in drugs trials","allowUgc":"false","headline":"How to make sure that the medicine goes down well","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"false","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T00:06:01.447Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/a0e8f2fea3ab406511