:"World news","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"theobserver","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/news/worldnews","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theobserver/news/worldnews","sectionName":"From the Observer"}]},{"id":"media/2015/nov/08/news-at-ten-battle-up-to-eleven-bbc-itv","type":"article","sectionId":"media","webTitle":"The News at Ten battle goes all the way up to eleven","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T09:00:00Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"849","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4e2xv","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/618fd35e65705c736ab7f7f62d7d872d0495bbb6/3_0_4923_2954/140.jpg","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"618fd35e65705c736ab7f7f62d7d872d0495bbb6\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/618fd35e65705c736ab7f7f62d7d872d0495bbb6/3_0_4923_2954/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Tom Bradby: a news personality, not just a reader.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Tom Bradby: a news personality, not just a reader.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Julian Simmonds//Rex Shutterstock</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>You can go mad obsessing over TV audience statistics. Has Tom Bradby’s new <em>News at Ten</em> hacked a chunk out of Huw Edwards’s BBC 10 o’clock figures as the ITV competitor soars towards 2 million a night? Or is the Broadcasting House version holding firm and doing “business as usual” – one claim from <a href=\"https://twitter.com/huwbbc/status/661511366537314305?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\" title=\"\">a chippy Huw tweet?</a> ITV <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/nov/04/itv-bbc-news-at-ten-huw-edwards-tom-bradby\" title=\"\">groans over BBC “arrogance”</a>. Reach for a broad brush and a stiff whisky.</p> <p>The answer – possibly – is that Bradby’s recent arrival has added 240,000 viewers in his first few weeks, and skimmed maybe 200,000 of them from Huw. But these are smallish shifts in a permanently shifting landscape (much conditioned by what’s on for the hour before 10pm). It’s best to conclude merely that the Bradby makeover has made a decent start, with many missing millions yet to go and Robert Peston yet to come. Forget instant successes or failures. Consider, rather, what the Bradby arrival means.</p> <p>Peter Donaldson, “the quintessential voice of Radio 4” according to Director General Hall, died last week. He read the news, beautifully, clearly, authoritatively. He was a news reader. Bradby on screen is a news presenter in the US tradition of Cronkite or Brokaw. He offers you the news through the prism of his personality. He seems to have written every word of his script and to deliver it with cheery authority. This is the news from Tom Bradby seen through the eyes of Tom Bradby. Which is where the BBC has a problem.</p> <p>Bradby is a TV professional journalist and highly experienced political correspondent turned presenter. So is Edwards. They both did major election night-and-day stints. They both know their stuff. But BBC <em>mores</em> in that giant red newsroom don’t allow the news at 10 with Huw (or Sophie) to major on personality pitches. The presenter is one of a seemingly mighty team spanning the globe; he or she is the means of delivering BBC majesty, not the end in itself. In short, a reader.</p> <p>Meanwhile the surrounding newsroom churns away 24/7. It is a factory welcoming shift workers to sit at its desks and address various audiences seemingly interchangeably. Reporters present and presenters report. There can’t be an aura of personal authority here because the context swamps it. This show – from Huw to Fiona to Reeta to Clive and beyond – is always on the road.</p> <p>In many ways that’s a huge advantage for Edwards and corporate resources. It’s where 4.4 or so million viewers a night come from and go to. But every big plus has its downside. Rolling news needs to keep on rolling. The factory has to keep on churning. ITV has its individual styles and outlets. BBC News can’t do cosy individuality. And what on earth would be the (rumoured) point of deserting the outward-and-visible evidence of a £1bn Broadcasting House refurbishment in order to move flagship news to a pokier studio somewhere downstairs? Pharaohs leave pyramids for Croydon crematorium.</p> <p>Bradby fans weren’t the only ones bashing the BBC last week. There was Kevin Sutcliffe from Vice, appearing before a House of Lords committee and describing corporation news as “beige”, “formal”, “stuffy” and “constrained”. It’s like the NHS, wanting to cover everything for everyone, he said. It ought to hold truth to power rather more zealously. There was Dorothy Byrne from Channel 4 saying the BBC must be brave. “They must not be politically correct, looking over their shoulders worrying.”</p> <p>A trifle unfair? Yes, if you reckon that Vice, with its video edge and TV ambitions, is more of a youth-oriented magazine show than a news service. Yes, if you acknowledge that <em>C4 News</em> with Jon Snow and Cathy Newman has more of an ad hoc licence to take risks. And yes, if you tot up the BBC nominations for this year’s British Journalism Awards. But it’s not unfair if the accusation of beigeness, in that great red <em>Hunger Games</em> set of a room, is allowed to take hold. BBC News 24/7 means you’ve seen the bulk of the 10 o’clock stint already at five, six and seven – the vox pops and production numbers rewound in a static studio setting. It can all seem a bit old hat, while Bradby has a chance to ring the changes.</p> <p>And there is very little sensible to be done about it. Moving the BBC main news to 9pm to appease Mr Secretary Whittingdale makes things worse. Telling Huw to put on a sweater and a smile doesn’t help much either. Quitting the £1bn temple of news transmission is a shot in the foot. ITV is doing what its doing because it’s different, and competing via that difference. Trying to do a Bradby at the Beeb means mixing beige with yellow – and only makes the tough, feisty job holding truth to power harder.</p> <p>Risk-taking? Tough stories that need telling straight? That’s difficult at charter renewal time and doubly difficult with Whittingdale and sundry Conservative press lords leering over your shoulder. But it’s still the best way of painting yourself out of a corner in bold new primary colours.</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10955151","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-08T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2402811","internalContentCode":"458348210","internalRevision":"50","publication":"The Observer","trailText":"The social media spat between ITV and Huw Edwards is just one manifestation of the pressure BBC news is under during a highly politicised charter renewal","allowUgc":"false","headline":"The News at Ten battle goes all the way up to eleven","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","byline":"Peter Preston","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T09:00:03.485Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/618fd35e65705c736ab7f7f62d7d872d0495bbb6/3_0_4923_2954/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"563cbc79e4b0cfe9766d06e3","newspaperPageNumber":"45","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-11T09:00:00Z","standfirst":"The social media spat between ITV and Huw Edwards is just one manifestation of the pressure BBC news is under during a highly politicised charter renewal","linkText":"The News at Ten battle goes all the way up to eleven","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-08T09:00:03.506Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/nov/08/news-at-ten-battle-up-to-eleven-bbc-itv","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/media/2015/nov/08/news-at-ten-battle-up-to-eleven-bbc-itv","sectionName":"Media","elements":[{"id":"618fd35e65705c736ab7f7f62d7d872d0495bbb6","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image