Reid/Evening Standard / eyevine","mediaId":"6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a/0_312_2756_1657/1000.jpg","width":"1000","height":"601"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a/0_312_2756_1657/500.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Evening Standard / eyevine. All Rights Reserved.","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a","suppliersReference":"eyevine","altText":"Campaigner for healthy models: Rosie Nelson","photographer":"Rebecca Reid","source":"Evening Standard / eyevine","credit":"Photograph: Rebecca Reid/Evening Standard / eyevine","mediaId":"6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a/0_312_2756_1657/500.jpg","width":"500","height":"301"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a/0_312_2756_1657/140.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Evening Standard / eyevine. All Rights Reserved.","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a","suppliersReference":"eyevine","altText":"Campaigner for healthy models: Rosie Nelson","photographer":"Rebecca Reid","source":"Evening Standard / eyevine","credit":"Photograph: Rebecca Reid/Evening Standard / eyevine","mediaId":"6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a/0_312_2756_1657/140.jpg","width":"140","height":"84"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a/0_312_2756_1657/2756.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Evening Standard / eyevine. All Rights Reserved.","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a","suppliersReference":"eyevine","altText":"Campaigner for healthy models: Rosie Nelson","photographer":"Rebecca Reid","source":"Evening Standard / eyevine","credit":"Photograph: Rebecca Reid/Evening Standard / eyevine","mediaId":"6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a/0_312_2756_1657/2756.jpg","width":"2756","height":"1657"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a/0_312_2756_1657/master/2756.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Evening Standard / eyevine. All Rights Reserved.","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a","suppliersReference":"eyevine","altText":"Campaigner for healthy models: Rosie Nelson","photographer":"Rebecca Reid","source":"Evening Standard / eyevine","credit":"Photograph: Rebecca Reid/Evening Standard / eyevine","mediaId":"6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/6d2effb4b94303846e6cf702c2ffd995aeb92a1a/0_312_2756_1657/master/2756.jpg","width":"2756","height":"1657","isMaster":"true"}}]}],"tags":[{"id":"theobserver/news/focus","webTitle":"In focus","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"theobserver","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/news/focus","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theobserver/news/focus","sectionName":"From the Observer"}]},{"id":"music/2015/nov/07/martyn-ware-synth-star-to-sonic-muralist-heaven-17","type":"article","sectionId":"music","webTitle":"From Heaven 17 to sonic muralist: how Martyn Ware wants to redefine art","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-07T14:32:03Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"1310","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4e2by","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/9122f9acd76fa4de85f400881ede4f56064a8964/0_1571_4560_2735/140.jpg","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"9122f9acd76fa4de85f400881ede4f56064a8964\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/9122f9acd76fa4de85f400881ede4f56064a8964/0_1571_4560_2735/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Heaven 17\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Martyn Ware, centre with fellow Heaven 17 members Ian Craig Marsh, left, and Glenn Gregory in 1982.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Sheila Rock/Rex Shutterstock</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>Ever wondered which particular sounds make Ludwigsburg in Germany, special? Or, for that matter, how the trendy Tietgenkollegiet student accommodation block in Copenhagen really ticks? Perhaps on a visit to the eccentric village of Portmeirion in Wales you have been unsettled by noises that slid out from between the buildings made famous by the 1960s television thriller <em>The Prisoner.</em></p> <p>Strange to say, but all these remote aural disturbances emanate from one place: the mind of the bloke from the Human League and Heaven 17. Martyn Ware, crown prince of the British synthesiser sound of the 1980s, has adopted the guise of an avant garde artist in his middle age. And this time there is no trace of subversive pretension, for there is nothing at all embarrassing, Ware argues, about being artistic – and Britain should wake up and realise that.</p> <p>“I find the world tries to make you feel guilty,” he said this weekend. “But anything artistic is undervalued in this country at the moment. The zeitgeist seems to dictate that artists should be grateful for any attention they get. Well, I just don’t buy that at all. It is really appalling and we are actually damaging our future prospects when people don’t support artistic endeavour.”</p> <p>On the north bank of the Thames in London this month stands a blue beach hut filled with memories of the British seaside. <em><a href=\"http://www.sightsoundandsea.co.uk/app/#/10/frame/2\">What Does the Sea Say?</a> </em>is a simple and effective repository of coastal sounds and recorded anecdotes and reflections collected by Ware. During the research stage, the hut was positioned at a trio of resorts and members of the public were invited to make vocal contributions.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"e8ecb2dbf0ed2d7ca224d43d59e2739532947700\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/e8ecb2dbf0ed2d7ca224d43d59e2739532947700/0_238_5616_3371/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Martyn Ware’s beach hut exhibition\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Martyn Ware’s What Does the Sea Say? beach hut exhibition.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Sam Roberts</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Now, as part of an exhibition called <a href=\"http://www.sightsoundandsea.co.uk/\">One and All</a> at Somerset House, Ware’s beach hut on the River Terrace is proving a popular attraction. He and his collaborators in the show, the poet Owen Shears and the visual artist Tania Kovats, were <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/nov/01/national-trust-virtual-coastline-london-digital-exhibition\">asked by the National Trust to recreate a coastal experience as part of its Coast 2015 initiative</a>.</p> <p>And although Ware still regularly performs sell-out shows with his fellow Heaven 17 band members, he is happy to combine the life of a venerable, gigging pop star with his day job as a “sonic muralist”. He and his colleagues at <a href=\"http://illustriouscompany.co.uk\">his company, Illustrious,</a> spend their time “reshaping memories and defining landscapes” with surround-sound installations all over Britain and Europe. So far Illustrious projects have stretched as far afield as Miami and Mexico. It is becoming something of an international crusade for the musician.</p> <p>“The sense of place is the theme that runs through much of what I do,” Ware said. “All my artistic output is aimed at the general public, with as little elitism as possible and as little pre-knowledge as possible. It is necessary to enjoy them. I try not to make it too wordy, for instance.”</p>       <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vIvx4xM-ehM\"                                                                        > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/vIvx4xM-ehM?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> <figcaption><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vIvx4xM-ehM&amp;feature=youtu.be\">Watch and listen to Martyn Ware’s sound sculpture What Does the Sea Say?</a></figcaption> </figure>   <p>Yet, while his art is intended to be accessible to all, Ware has no problem defending the heightened aesthetics of his approach: “It sounds pretentious I know, but I want to maintain that creative attitude and to take it still further.” Artistic effort is now frequently viewed as a frippery, he believes, because too many people believe they can only find meaning in their lives by earning more money. “This means the artistic world is regarded as something quite nice to have – a bit like a nice car or wearing a nice suit – a luxury, but one which is not an essential part of the soul. I don’t want any part of that and that is one of the reasons why I am moving away from the commercial side of the sound work I do. I got sick of people in the corporate world having no imagination.”</p> <p>Ware, 59, now takes only those commissions that seem creatively worthwhile. Visitors to Liverpool this spring who wandered through the shopping centre will have <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/may/24/liverpool-culture-festival-revival-historic-liners-one-magnificent-city\">heard the sound of transatlantic travel Ware constructed,</a> taking them on a journey from the docks to Manhattan and back. He regards it as a process of painting images in people’s minds with a palette of selected noise.</p> <p>Growing up in Sheffield, the young Ware befriended Glenn Gregory, later the lead singer of Heaven 17, and tried, without success, to get him to join his band, which combined electronics and pop music. Philip Oakey, a school friend of Ware’s, became the singer of the group which soon adopted the name the Human League.</p> <p>Oakey, who still performs with Joanne Catherall and Susan Ann Sulley, found success with the single Don’t You Want Me? as Ware left with keyboard player Ian Craig Marsh to set up a new band, Heaven 17.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"61ae937cfef7f86431f97625431ce3073da3b2de\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/61ae937cfef7f86431f97625431ce3073da3b2de/0_0_4500_3000/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Martyn Ware, right, with fellow contributors to the National Trust’s One and All exhibition, Tania Kovats and Benjamin Wigley.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"667\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Martyn Ware, right, with fellow contributors to the National Trust’s One and All exhibition, Tania Kovats and Benjamin Wigley.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Sam Roberts</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Ware became a record producer in 1986, working on highly lucrative albums including <em>Introducing the Hardline According to Terence Trent D’Arby</em> and Tina Turner’s <em>Let’s Stay Together</em>.</p> <p>“From that period until around 1999 my name appeared as producer on 50 million records, but the work was getting to be more and more about new boy bands and I thought, ‘Even if I am successful with this stuff, then I am just going to be asked to do more’. Around then, as luck would have it, I fell in love with the notion of surround-sound when I was asked to be a consultant to the National Centre for Popular Music in Sheffield. They had the idea of a surround-sound auditorium.”</p> <p>From 2000 to the present day he has “carried on with Heaven 17 as a kind of a sidebar, with my real passion making immersive soundscapes”.</p> <p>Ware now lives in north London and has a studio in King’s Cross. Performances with Heaven 17 allow him to play music from an era which he regards as the last truly innovative heyday of British music. “There’s a lot of 80s-influenced sound around again, but I honestly think the late 70s and early 80s were a golden age. Britpop put up no contest.”</p> <p>He has, he says, loved each bit of his career and regards himself as lucky to have made enough money at times to survive, but not so much that he doesn’t have to work. “I am not that flush, but the impetus to try new things would not be quite the same if I didn’t need money. With a family I have got plenty of overheads, but that is all right as it keeps me wanting to take jobs. I can’t imagine anything worse than not working. I dread the day when I’m not capable of working. Maybe it is part of my Sheffield background and my dad coming from the steelworks. I love what I do and want to keep being useful as long as possible.”</p> <h2>MARTYN WARE: THE CHARTS AND THE ARTS</h2> <p>■ 1977: Sheffield-born Martyn Ware asks his charismatic friend Phil Oakey, a snappy dresser working as a hospital porter, to join his band making a new synthesised pop sound in the Human League.</p> <p>■ 1980: Ware leaves the band and Heaven 17, after much critical acclaim, finally chart with Temptation, a “song about sex”, in 1983.<br /></p>       <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e7_Rc7m_smQ\"                                                                        > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/e7_Rc7m_smQ?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> <figcaption><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e7_Rc7m_smQ\">Listen to Temptation by Heaven 17</a></figcaption> </figure>   <p>■ The 1980s see Ware produce a series of albums for singers including Terence Trent D’Arby and Tina Turner.<br /></p> <p>■ In the late 90s, Ware is asked to help create a surround-sound auditorium at Sheffield’s now defunct National Centre for Popular Music.<br /></p> <p>■ Ware goes on to develop soundscapes for international projects, including the Tales from the Bridge installation, an hour-long recorded loop of ambient electronic music merged with a spoken narrative about London, for the Cultural Olympiad in 2012.<br /></p>","internalOctopusCode":"10957831","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-08T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2403102","internalContentCode":"458350940","internalRevision":"182","publication":"The Observer","trailText":"The synth star of the 80s wants to make avant garde art accessible to all – and says Britain shouldn’t be embarrassed about creativity","allowUgc":"false","headline":"From Heaven 17 to sonic muralist: how Martyn Ware wants to redefine art","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","byline":"Vanessa Thorpe","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-07T14:32:03.706Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/9122f9acd76fa4de85f400881ede4f56064a8964/0_1571_4560_2735/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"563d1a5ee4b0ace666f8b8ad","newspaperPageNumber":"18","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-10T14:32:07Z","standfirst":"<p>The synth star of the 80s wants to make avant garde art accessible to all – and says Britain shouldn’t be embarrassed about creativity</p>","linkText":"From Heaven 17 to sonic muralist: how Martyn Ware wants to redefine art","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-13T12:43:08.105Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/nov/07/martyn-ware-synth-star-to-sonic-muralist-heaven-17","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/music/2015/nov/07/martyn-ware-synth-star-to-sonic-muralist-heaven-17","sect