\" height=\"601\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Towering ambition: wealthy investors welcome the chance to invest in such great British institutions as Oxford University. </span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Mark Sykes/JAI/Corbis</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>Just as the French political elite is overwhelmingly educated at the École nationale d’administration, so their English counterparts are overwhelming educated at Oxford University. There the similarity once stopped.</p> <p>France has more than its fair share of conspiracy theorists, but you didn’t have to join them to worry about the tight circle of <em>énarques</em> at the top of the republic. They grew up together, slept together, learned the same rules and had the same teachers. They came from a school established at Charles de Gaulle’s instigation to train France’s rulers. Only <a href=\"http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/d76b5fcc-b83f-11e2-bd62-00144feabdc0.html#axzz3qnRVMQxP\" title=\"\">80 students a year graduate</a> and what they are taught is everybody’s business.</p> <p>By contrast, Oxford University’s politics, philosophy and economics course was not established to create a ruling class. I am a PPE graduate – who isn’t, darling? – and can testify that there wasn’t then, and is not now, anything resembling an Oxford ideology. My teachers ranged from Marxists to free marketeers. Most had no discernible political views, ground down as they were by the joyless task of trying to make their students think clearly. It was a pleasure to have met them, although I worry sometimes that the feeling was not always reciprocated.</p> <p>Oxford’s triumph is the victory of a self-organising system, not a Gaullist masterplan. Ambitious young people who want to become politicians see that successful politicians have studied PPE. They apply to Oxford and become successful politicians themselves. Success breeds success and the machine feeds itself.</p> <p>You could say that Oxford’s dominance was acquired, like the British empire, in a fit of absent-mindedness. Not any more, I think. Oxford was never just a university for the British elite. In the mid-2000s, 5% of the world’s foreign ministers had studied at <a href=\"http://www.sant.ox.ac.uk\" title=\"\">St Antony’s,</a> Oxford’s postgraduate college for political studies. In 2012, Oxford opened the <a href=\"http://www.bsg.ox.ac.uk/\" title=\"\">Blavatnik School of Government</a>. The oligarch from Putin’s Russia, who now lives in London, secured the honour of having his name on the gate when he gave the <a href=\"http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/01/20/the-billionaires-playlist\" title=\"\">university £75m.</a> “Fifty or 60 graduates of Oxford have been prime ministers and presidents, not only in this country but around the world,” he explained.<a href=\"http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/01/20/the-billionaires-playlist\" title=\"\"> </a>He wanted to see more like them. What these young ladies and gentlemen are taught, in other words, is now a matter of interest not just for Britain but for the planet.</p> <p>I have no grudge against Len Blavatnik. His school of government may produce searching examinations of Putin’s control of the media and suppression of the opposition in Russia and of crony capitalism the world over. He may privately despise the Kremlin regime, but go along with it in public, as anyone who wants to do business in Russia must.</p> <p>But if you can judge an oligarch by the quality of his opponents, Oxford is in trouble. Last week, better and braver people than Blavatnik will ever be told the <em>Guardian</em> that the university <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/education/2015/nov/03/oxford-university-accused-over-oligarch-len-blavatnik-75m-donation\" title=\"\">“should stop selling its reputation and prestige to Putin’s associates”. </a></p> <p>Among the protesters were dissidents who are worth more than any billionaire. Vladimir Bukovsky, who was jailed by the KGB for revealing that the Soviet Union had decided it was insane to question the glories of socialism and sent its “mad” critics to psychiatric hospitals for treatment. Alongside him was the magnificent Andrei Sannikov, whom I met when he was an optimistic Belarusian politician who still believed that his country could be freed, only to have his hopes destroyed when the dictatorship jailed him for disputing a rigged election in 2010.</p> <p>You need not only weigh the leading players’ characters to get a feel for this dispute. We know that <a href=\"http://www.ft.com/cms/s/b276dcc0-0893-11e2-b37e-00144feabdc0,Authorised=false.html?siteedition=uk&amp;_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2Fb276dcc0-0893-11e2-b37e-00144feabdc0.html%3Fsiteedition%3Duk&amp;_i_referer=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.co.uk%2F376e4bf5d13c456f0a70f0df40f7360f&amp;classification=conditional_standard&amp;iab=barrier-app#axzz3qnRVMQxP\" title=\"\">Saudi Arabia has donated</a> to Islamic studies centres at Oxford and elsewhere. Whatever their scholarly virtues, they are not noted for their attacks on the myths and brutalities of Wahabbi theology. We have seen the London School of Economics demonstrate how soft dictatorial power works in academia. When Anthony Giddens and other academics ran a “North Africa research programme” funded by Colonel Gaddafi they fawned over their paymaster.</p> <p>To all of which one of my weary dons might say, so what? Walk round the university and you gaze at ancient colleges without thinking that they were funded by medieval warlords and Henry VIII’s dissolution of the monasteries. You may admire, too, Hawksmoor’s beautiful Codrington library at All Souls without thinking that it was built with <a href=\"http://abajantourgirlexploringbarbados.blogspot.co.uk/2010/05/barbados-african-slave-trade-and-sugar_20.html\" title=\"\">money from Caribbean slave labour</a>.</p> <p>It’s true, as the French say, that “behind every great fortune lies a great crime”. But British institutions are more impressed by the Russian saying that “you should never ask about the first million”. No one cares where Oxford’s colleges came from, just as no one cares that redbrick universities across Britain were funded by the masters of Victorian capitalism. Today the British, who were once colonisers, are now colonised. Oligarchies and dictatorships are where the money is. Is Oxford meant to turn it down?</p> <p>With a 900-year history, the university can take the long view. It understands that institutions survive and do good long after their once mighty benefactors have joined those they robbed in the dust. It’s always been that way. Except that in the 20th century it was not. The government funded research and academic expansion. There was, politicians reasoned, a national interest in having expert independent advice about dangerous powers such as Russia, just as there was a national interest in having health researchers who weren’t bankrolled by conglomerates providing advice on dangerous drugs and diets.</p> <p>The state ought to intervene today to prevent foreign powers exploiting British universities, in the same way as it should legislate to stop the epidemic of neurotic priggishness that drives student unions to ban speakers who diverge from the party line.</p> <p>I can’t see it happening. When universities take millions from Russian oligarchs or Saudi theocrats they are doing what the Conservatives want them to do: relieving the burden on the taxpayer by establishing a public-private partnership. How can a government, which is selling national assets to China on appallingly bad terms, tell universities not to sell their integrity? How can a government that wants to stop free speech, which does not incite violence, condemn student fanatics who do the same?</p> <p>If you want to see David Cameron’s big society, go to Oxford. You can’t say what you think, particularly when what you are thinking of asking is: who’s paying the piper?</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10958898","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-08T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2403168","internalContentCode":"458351555","internalRevision":"159","publication":"The Observer","trailText":"As protesters criticise Oxford for accepting cash from a Putin crony, the state should stop foreign powers exploiting Britain’s great educational institutions","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Tainted money that belittles Oxford University","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","byline":"Nick Cohen","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T14:18:08.793Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404/0_0_7277_4372/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"563ddd41e4b0ace666f8b91f","newspaperPageNumber":"38","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-11T12:00:00+00:00","standfirst":"<p>As protesters criticise Oxford for accepting cash from a Putin crony, the state should stop foreign powers exploiting Britain’s great educational institutions</p>","linkText":"Tainted money that belittles Oxford University | Nick Cohen","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-09T08:27:02.578Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/08/tainted-money-belittles-oxford-university","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/08/tainted-money-belittles-oxford-university","sectionName":"Comment is free","elements":[{"id":"1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404/0_0_7277_4372/2000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Corbis.  All Rights Reserved.","picdarUrn":"GD*53548384","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404","suppliersReference":"63258354","altText":"Towering ambition: w