is.  All Rights Reserved.","picdarUrn":"GD*53548384","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404","suppliersReference":"63258354","altText":"Towering ambition: wealthy investors welcome the chance to invest in such great British institutions as Oxford University.","photographer":"Mark Sykes","source":"JAI/Corbis","credit":"Photograph: Mark Sykes/JAI/Corbis","mediaId":"1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404/0_0_7277_4372/140.jpg","width":"140","height":"84"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404/0_0_7277_4372/7277.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Corbis.  All Rights Reserved.","picdarUrn":"GD*53548384","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404","suppliersReference":"63258354","altText":"Towering ambition: wealthy investors welcome the chance to invest in such great British institutions as Oxford University.","photographer":"Mark Sykes","source":"JAI/Corbis","credit":"Photograph: Mark Sykes/JAI/Corbis","mediaId":"1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404/0_0_7277_4372/7277.jpg","width":"7277","height":"4372"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404/0_0_7277_4372/master/7277.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Corbis.  All Rights Reserved.","picdarUrn":"GD*53548384","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404","suppliersReference":"63258354","altText":"Towering ambition: wealthy investors welcome the chance to invest in such great British institutions as Oxford University.","photographer":"Mark Sykes","source":"JAI/Corbis","credit":"Photograph: Mark Sykes/JAI/Corbis","mediaId":"1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/1882e39d31e3d262114fc5ed7482826ad9688404/0_0_7277_4372/master/7277.jpg","width":"7277","height":"4372","isMaster":"true"}}]}],"tags":[{"id":"theobserver/news/comment","webTitle":"Comment","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"theobserver","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/news/comment","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theobserver/news/comment","sectionName":"From the Observer"}]},{"id":"commentisfree/2015/nov/08/national-health-service-deficit-junior-doctors","type":"article","sectionId":"commentisfree","webTitle":"The NHS has social objectives as well as economic ones. Can we reconcile them? | Jennifer Dixon","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T00:06:02Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"1268","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4e2ek","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/73a8e96547d2f3a578f045c16669dd9078803729/1376_427_3538_2122/140.jpg","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"73a8e96547d2f3a578f045c16669dd9078803729\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/73a8e96547d2f3a578f045c16669dd9078803729/1376_427_3538_2122/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Operating theatre staff at Birmingham’s Queen Elizabeth Hospital.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Operating theatre staff at Birmingham’s Queen Elizabeth Hospital.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Christopher Furlong/Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>Look beyond the headlines is always wise advice. The main story in the NHS at present appears to be a standoff between Jeremy Hunt, the health secretary, and junior doctors and the BMA on pay and working conditions. But the real story has far more to do with pace of the financial squeeze on the public sector to reduce the fiscal deficit by 2020-21. And this is a <em>political</em> choice.</p> <p>The NHS is used to an average real-terms growth of 4% per year. Since 2009-10, the figure has been cut to about 1% per annum – the most sustained period of parsimony since the <a href=\"http://www.nhs.uk/NHSEngland/thenhs/nhshistory/Pages/NHShistory1948.aspx\" title=\"\">NHS was formed in 1948</a>.</p> <p>With population rising, this has meant a real cut in per capita expenditure. Across the OECD, only Ireland, Greece, Portugal and Spain, countries subject to IMF intervention, have had lower growth rates. And as a share of GDP, NHS and private spend on healthcare in the UK, at 8.5%, is low compared to most advanced countries in western Europe, averaging over 10%. The NHS is not only cheap, but is also under a tighter fiscal straitjacket than elsewhere.</p> <p>To be sure, spending on the NHS has been protected relative to deep cuts elsewhere. Funding for adult social care between 2009-10 and 2013-14 was cut by almost one-third in real terms. The impact is harsh – an estimated 400,000 fewer people are now eligible for support. Reduced payments by local authorities to social care providers are <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/oct/31/half-care-homes-could-close-cash-crisis\" title=\"\">pushing the sector to breaking</a> point. The impact on the NHS is increased demand for care because of lack of social support.</p> <p>The result is that 80% of NHS trusts are in deficit and, along with general practices, are under significant pressure. The NHS as a whole in England is facing an estimated £2bn shortfall by the end of the financial year on a £116bn revenue budget. Whereas in the past NHS hospitals may have cut corners on quality to balance the books, published information inspections and ratings of care by the <a href=\"http://www.cqc.org.uk/\" title=\"\">Care Quality Commission</a> reduce the scope to do so.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>Tthe NHS can't shut down a loss-making plant, turn off unwanted demand, increase profit-making lines</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>There are now signs of deteriorating access to care, particularly for mental health services, and waiting times for elective and emergency care are growing. Factor in a cold winter and a crisis is inevitable. The scale and extent of the deficits is so large as to be less a problem for individual providers and more a political problem.</p> <p>The government has committed to “increasing the NHS budget by a minimum of £8bn to 2020-21”. Given the fiscal straitjacket, it is hard to justify further increases since this would mean even deeper cuts elsewhere. And social care must be a priority for any extra investment announced in the forthcoming spending review. Relative to projected demands and costs of the NHS, this leaves a gap of £22bn by 2020-21.</p> <p>Faced with these pressures, the NHS does not have the same room for manoeuvre as a business. It cannot easily shut down a loss-making plant, turn off unwanted demand, increase profit-making lines. The NHS has social objectives as well as economic ones – to provide equal access to comprehensive care free at the point of need. That is the root of its strong support among the British people, consistently strong support that spills into the streets when services are threatened.</p> <p>The NHS is also far larger, more complex and riskier than almost any other enterprise in the UK, with 1.4 million highly educated staff, most of whom work on the shopfloor. And, as the current <a href=\"https://www.england.nhs.uk/tag/simon-stevens/\" title=\"\">chief of NHS England, Simon Stevens,</a> quipped to the health select committee about a report on NHS management by the former chief of M&amp;S, running the NHS is harder than selling underwear. Quick-fix solutions beloved (though not exclusively) by politicians are often simple, elegant… and wrong.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"77a3eda585e9abae49ac1a1f8e6b8032491e2239\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/77a3eda585e9abae49ac1a1f8e6b8032491e2239/1031_0_2275_2849/799.jpg\" alt=\"Jeremy Hunt should be more cautious about demoralising junior doctors.\" width=\"799\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Jeremy Hunt should be more cautious about demoralising junior doctors.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Suzanne Plunkett/Reuters</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>In the short term, there are options. Pay is two-thirds of the total cost of the NHS and the government has already announced that public sector pay will rise just 1% a year in cash terms. This is below forecast inflation and below recent trends in private sector pay. Without careful management, there is a major risk of this leading to further increases in the number of dearer temporary and agency staff, although recent steps have been taken to cap the total agency bill per provider and maximum pay rate. The room to cut staff numbers is limited, especially with the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/oct/15/two-thirds-hospitals-substandard-care-care-quality-commission\" title=\"\">Care Quality Commission reporting 13% of hospitals inadequate on the safety front</a>, with staff levels a key factor. Holding down the national tariff that the NHS pays for services is another policy already pursued.</p> <p>Whether or not you agree with this government’s spending ambitions, in each of the past 20 years in all of the <a href=\"https://stats.oecd.org/glossary/detail.asp?ID=6805\" title=\"\">EU-15 countries</a>, healthcare costs have outstripped GDP growth. The NHS is sustainable but the answer is to improve efficiency on a wide scale, which includes preventing ill health. Earlier this year in the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/apr/19/britain-uncovered-survey-attitudes-beliefs-britons-2015\" title=\"\">2015 British Social Attitudes survey</a>, 51% of the public reported seeing waste in the NHS. To meet the £22bn gap and if pay increases are held to 1% , the NHS will need efficiency growth of 2% a year in real terms. This is much higher than the long-term historic rate of 1% a year and substantially higher than the recent rate for acute hospitals of 0.4%.</p> <p>Achieving efficiency on this scale will be complicated and a long, hard grind. Superficial responses such as “more competition”, “game-changing technologies, “strong-arm management”, “fewer managers”and “more performance incentives” might sound good, but won’t do.</p> <p>Instead, a coherent approach developed with the staff at the front line, where efficiencies will largely be delivered, is crucial. There are some examples. The <a href=\"https://www.england.nhs.uk/ourwork/futurenhs/nhs-five-year-forward-view-web-version/5yfv-exec-sum/\" title=\"\">Five Year Forward View, </a>published a year ago, is helping to develop new models of care involving preventing illness and dependency. Lord Carter is leading an initiative with hospitals using data to show where they could make savings from procurement to treatments, estimating £5bn potential savings.</p> <p>But these important initiatives look underpowered against the reality on the ground: overstretched staff with no support to make improvements; high turnover of senior management (average time on post for a hospital chief executive is 300 days); administration costs very low at 2.5%; no funds to invest for change; deficits too large to feel they can be acted on; public health a Cinderella service. Clearly, reducing the deficits to manageable proportions is an immediate priority, most likely through a “bung”, perhaps by raiding the capital budget. But more important in the medium term is a dedicated transformation fund for the NHS, argued for by both the Health Foundation and King’s Fund.</p> <p>Crucially, it is the clinical and managerial staff on the very front line of the NHS and the public who are most able to see what changes are needed, not policy-makers, and they need to be fully involved in finding solutions. The usual assumption in Whitehall is that NHS staff, especially front-line clinicians, won’t change and craft policies to make them. This is being played out in part in the current dispute with junior doctors, but there is plenty of motivation and talent to find solutions.</p> <p>A more effective approach would be to trust and support the staff and commit to mass engagement, rather than hope for a quick fix. Another reason why Jeremy Hunt should be more cautious about demoralising junior doctors.</p> <p><em>Dr Jennifer Dixon is chief executive of the Health Foundation</em></p> <h2>HEALTH SPECIAL</h2>","internalOctopusCode":"10959071","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-08T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2403182","internalContentCode":"458351606","internalRevision":"86","publication":"The Observer","trailText":"The health service will be £22bn in the red by 2020 and only clinical staff-led efficiencies can save it","allowUgc":"false","headline":"The NHS has social objectives as well as economic ones. Can we reconcile them?","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","byline":"Jennifer Dixon","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T00:06:01.851Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/73a8e96547d2f3a578f045c16669dd9078803729/1376_427_3538_2122/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"563deccce4b05e53c04d4c0d","newspaperPageNumber":"39","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-11T00:06:02Z","standfirst":"The health service will be £22bn in the red by 2020 and only clinical staff-led efficiencies can save it","linkText":"The NHS has social objectives as well as economic ones. Can we reconcile them? | Jennifer Dixon","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-08T00:06:02.000Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/08/national-health