image\" data-media-id=\"3a331dc854855a279c96f54198606b2d28020dc6\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/3a331dc854855a279c96f54198606b2d28020dc6/0_0_5760_3459/1000.jpg\" alt=\"As evidence mounts of a terror attack, Egyptian soldiers guard the entrance to Sharm el-Sheikh international airport. \" width=\"1000\" height=\"601\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">As evidence of a terror attack continues to mount, Egyptian soldiers guard the entrance to Sharm el-Sheikh international airport. </span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Thomas Hartwell/AP</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>The crash of the Russian A321-200 Airbus in Sinai last Saturday, which killed all 224 people on board, is turning into one of the defining moments of the worldwide struggle against jihadi terrorism. Evidence that the plane was destroyed by an onboard bomb and not by a technical fault, pilot error or structural failure, is mounting by the day.</p> <p>French investigators say the aircraft’s black box<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/06/putin-suspends-russian-flights-to-egypt-after-sinai-plane-crash\" title=\"\"> recorded a sudden explosion</a>. US officials, referring to intercepts probably obtained by GCHQ’s Troodos listening post in Cyprus, say they overheard “chatter” between Islamic State terrorists in Sinai and Syria pointing to a bomb plot. American satellites <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/06/putin-suspends-russian-flights-to-egypt-after-sinai-plane-crash\" title=\"\">reportedly spotted a flash</a> at the moment the plane disappeared off radar screens. Russian complaints that Britain acted rashly by suggesting early last week that a bomb caused the disaster have faded amid repeated Isis boasts of responsibility. Vladimir Putin eventually followed David Cameron’s lead in suspending flights between Russia and Egypt while security was reviewed at Sharm el-Sheikh, where the plane took off, and other Egyptian airports. The US, similarly slow off the mark, has also tightened security.</p> <p>The fact that Russia and Egypt continue to cast doubt on suggestions the attack was mounted by the Isis affiliate in Sinai, known as Sinai Province, is both understandable and disingenuous. Putin knows that if he admits Isis did it, the Russian public will see it as <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/05/sinai-plane-crash-putin-military-adventurism-syria-analysis\" title=\"\">pay-back for his recklessly provocative military intervention</a> in Syria last month – and may blame him personally for this and any future terror attacks. For this reason alone, Russian obfuscation may continue.</p> <p>The Egyptian authorities, from President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi down, likewise understand that irrefutable proof that terrorists penetrated security at Sharm el-Sheikh would be disastrous for the country’s reputation and vital tourism industry, so they persist in talking up less disturbing scenarios while claiming they have been kept in the dark.</p> <p>There are other signs of a continuing, face-saving reluctance to call a bomb a bomb. The White House, for example, fears an Isis success on this scale would highlight Barack Obama’s failed pledge to “degrade and destroy” the organisation.</p> <p>Worse still, confirmation that Isis blew up the plane would give the group an enormous boost, marking a watershed moment in the rapid evolution of a terror gang few had heard of 18 months ago. Until recently, Isis has been largely focused on consolidating a “caliphate” in northern Iraq and Syria. Its recruiting efforts have centred on drawing in foreign jihadis to defend this territory.</p> <p>In contrast, a big, off-base attack like that in Sinai would suggest Isis is pursuing wider ambitions and greater strategic and operational capabilities. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/05/isis-word-sinai-plane-crash-catastrophic\" title=\"\">If it did destroy the Russian plane</a>, it will have been responsible for the second deadliest terrorist attack since 9/11, the most deadly being the 2004 school massacre in Beslan in the Russian Caucasus by Chechen Islamist separatists that killed 385 people. This prospectively puts Isis in the same international terror league as al-Qaida.</p> <p>While al-Qaida and its leadership have been significantly degraded since 2001 by US attrition, Isis is led by its very own Osama bin Laden figure, the self-styled caliph, Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi. Known as the “invisible sheikh”, Baghdadi, unlike Bin Laden, has apparently survived several attempts to kill him. And while there have been numerous al-Qaida attempts to blow up civilian aircraft in midair, including a 2006 plot targeting aircraft flying from Britain to the US, none, apart from the 9/11 hijackings, has succeeded.</p> <p>Isis thus appears to have dramatically trumped its older rival, an achievement that can only increase its attraction to would-be jihadis across the Muslim sphere. Here lies the bigger, long-term danger arising from last week’s events. If Isis, working through an affiliate in Sinai, can cause such instant mayhem in Egypt, then what is to stop it attempting similar atrocities elsewhere in the world? The sobering truth is that this feared expansion is already under way.</p> <p>Israel is at obvious risk. Sinai Province, formerly known as Ansar Beit al-Maqdis (Supporters of Jerusalem), reportedly comprises mostly indigenous Bedouin fighters but also Palestinian militants from Gaza. It has a history of attacks on Israeli targets. Further north, suicide bombings in Ankara that killed more than 100 people last month were attributed to Isis by Turkey’s president. To the south and west, the group has expanded into Libya, perpetrating trademark killings of Christians and other “unbelievers”. Few in Britain will have forgotten last June’s horrific <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3140454/Tourists-run-lives-Tunisian-beach-gunman-carries-attack-outside-hotel-packed-Britons.html\" title=\"\"> beach killings </a>by an Isis gunman in Sousse, Tunisia.</p> <p>The spreading Isis menace is not confined to the Middle East. Reports suggest a growing contest for status, recruits and influence in Afghanistan, pitting Isis against al-Qaida and the Taliban. A similar evolution is taking place in Bangladesh, one of the world’s most populous Muslim countries. A recent spate of random machete attacks on westerners has exacerbated worries about the murders of secular bloggers. Although Dhaka officials blame local Islamists, there are well-founded fears that Isis (as well as al-Qaida) is organising there, and among India’s large Muslim minority.</p> <p>The underlying causes of the expanding jihadi phenomenon have been well rehearsed, but western countries, Britain included, appear no closer to finding effective answers. The civil war or “fitna” within Islam between hardline Sunni and Shia Muslims, the chronic poverty and underdevelopment experienced by most Muslim countries, and the overall failure of the Arab spring to dislodge corrupt, authoritarian and undemocratic regimes, such as Sisi’s in Egypt, are all powerful triggers for revolt. Then there is the long, damaging – and unfinished – history of western interventionism in the Middle East.</p> <p>Isis has openly declared itself at war with Britain, its allies and now Russia, too. It must be rooted out or else more terrible outrages may follow. This may ultimately involve a truly international, UN-authorised combined military operation in Syria (in contrast to the Bush/Blair intervention in Iraq). It would see the west, Russia and the Arab powers joining together to suppress Isis, end the civil war and refugee crisis, and achieve a political settlement. An international menace requires a truly international response.</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10959350","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11