.jpg\" alt=\"Children are particularly vulnerable at major stations.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Children are particularly vulnerable at major stations.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: David Pearson/Rex</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>Railway station staff, including retail workers and ticket collectors, will be given training on how to spot vulnerable children following warnings that public transport is a hotspot for young people who have run away from home and are at risk of exploitation.</p> <p>The initiative follows research by British Transport police (BTP) which recorded incidents involving 6,000 vulnerable children in stations last year, including those running away or suspected of being a victim of crime.</p> <p>Andy McCullough, director of policy and public affairs at the <a href=\"https://www.railwaychildren.org.uk\">charity Railway Children</a>, which has developed the training with BTP, said the programme would help to identify children who often go unnoticed.</p> <p>“If we’re going to learn anything from child disasters such as the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/climbie\">Victoria Climbié</a> or <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/baby-p\">Baby Peter</a> cases, it’s that communities and the public had lots of opportunities to make interventions but didn’t – they were either too scared or didn’t know who to speak to,” he said. </p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/2015/nov/05/parents-children-online-search-history-microsoft-windows-10-privacy\">Parents, is it OK to spy on your child's online search history?</a> </p> </aside>  <p>“We’re not all social workers and we’re not asking people to make huge interventions – we’re just asking them to be a bit more courageous and a bit more sensitive.”</p> <p>About 100,000 under-16s run away each year, with many becoming vulnerable to grooming and sexual exploitation. Red light areas outside major stations are a particular concern, said McCullough.</p> <p>Station staff will be asked to look for signs that a child may be vulnerable, such as loitering for a long time on their own or wearing school uniform at the weekend.</p> <p>Louise Ellman, Labour MP for Liverpool Riverside and chair of the Commons transport select committee, said the safety of children in stations had been neglected.</p> <p>“Stations are places where vulnerable young people often congregate,” she said.</p> <p>“They may be running away from their homes or it may simply be a place where they meet others. Often the perception is that the young people involved could be a source of trouble, when in reality they are overwhelmingly vulnerable young people who need help.”</p> <p>A <a href=\"http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmselect/cmtran/428/42807.htm#a9\">report published last year</a> by the transport select committee recommended that BTP should be brought in line with other police forces, which set targets to assess how well they support vulnerable children. </p> <p>Railway Children is now working with BTP, operating companies and charities to ensure incidents are reported and that more emergency accommodation is made available for 16- and 17-year-olds.</p> <p>Paul Crowther, chief constable of BTP, said train staff would play a crucial role in reporting unusual behaviour.</p> <p>“They can be our eyes and ears as they go about their day-to-day work by providing us with the information we need to recognise signs of vulnerability or potential exploitation.”</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10959530","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-08T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2403235","internalContentCode":"458352002","internalRevision":"102","publication":"The Observer","trailText":"Railway wor