Id":"global","webTitle":"Egg freezing is developing but more knowledge is needed | Letters","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T00:04:02Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"812","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4exzf","secureThumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/6e514edc1a3c673fbadd0edcc69c5d6d393c51c2/0_265_4668_2799/140.jpg","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"6e514edc1a3c673fbadd0edcc69c5d6d393c51c2\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/6e514edc1a3c673fbadd0edcc69c5d6d393c51c2/0_265_4668_2799/1000.jpg\" alt=\"The artificial insemination of a human egg.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The artificial insemination of a human egg.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Alamy</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>In your recent article and commentary on egg freezing (“<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/oct/24/egg-freezing-fertility-insurance-clinics-conference\" title=\"\">Egg freezing is the tempting option if you’re desperate for a child; but can women be sure it’s the right choice?</a>”, News), you make assertions about the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) that require clarification.</p> <p>You say that we publish “no data on success rates by clinic”, but fail to note that, while there has been an increase in the number of women freezing their eggs, there have not yet been enough cycles performed using those eggs to produce any meaningful outcome data. The very purpose of freezing is to use eggs later and many that have been frozen have yet to be used.</p> <p>Freezing is a developing technique and there are difficulties in presenting the data in a manner helpful to women. For example, the recent fast-freeze “vitrification” process appears to be overtaking older slow-freezing techniques in popularity and success. But its newness means no substantial data analysis can yet be done. Do we present the slow-freeze data anyway?</p> <p>These are difficult decisions and we are wary of publishing inaccurate information that is not useful to patients. However, we recognise egg freezing is gaining in prominence and we will be introducing egg freezing data to our fertility trends reports.</p> <p>Lastly, comments that we are “making no serious attempt to control the vast fees charged” fundamentally misunderstands our powers. We are statutorily tasked with ensuring public and private fertility services are provided to a high standard, but have no powers to control or investigate cost. The requirement by us that clinics give patients a costed treatment plan in advance, introduced in 2009, is at the boundary of what we can do.</p> <p><strong>Peter Thompson</strong><br />Chief executive, Human Fertilisation &amp; Embryology Authority<br /></p> <h2><strong>True perils of over-population</strong></h2> <p>The <em>Observer</em> misses the point about increasing populations (“<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/01/observer-editorial-britain-china-population-challenges\" title=\"\">World population: it’s not just about numbers</a>”, leading article). Please don’t muddy the waters with talk about ageing populations and immigration. Population cannot continue to increase indefinitely.</p> <p>Increasing population is a global problem since everybody must be fed, watered and housed. The resources to enable this are finite. More people, especially in developed countries, mean more greenhouse gases, pollution and climate change. Because people everywhere are now mobile, we need to take a global view and not just consider one or two countries in isolation.</p> <p>There might seem to be some benefits in increasing the population in some countries in the short term, but even that relies on the questionable premise that continued economic growth is both desirable and possible.</p> <p><strong>Dr Brian Curwain</strong><br /><strong>Dr Mary Davies</strong><br />Christchurch, Dorset<br /></p> <h2><strong>BBC’s fate is in its own hands</strong></h2> <p>Nick Cohen makes an impressively passionate plea on behalf of the BBC (“<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/oct/08/comment.theobserver1\" title=\"\">Traduced by all sides, who will defend the BBC?</a>”, Comment). Unfortunately, the central premise of his article is mistaken. The government has not imposed a 20% cut on the BBC. It has given the BBC five years’ notice that, as from 2020, it will no longer fund free TV licences for the over-75s. It will be entirely up to the BBC how and whether it chooses to collect licences from them after 2020.</p> <p>It is true that, in the period up to 2020, the BBC has agreed to part fund this concession, in exchange for other cash benefits, such as index-linking of the licence fee level, which equal that cost (and which will continue to benefit the BBC after 2020). But any change in the basic licence fee level will simply match any reduced set of obligations, so it remains the case that the supposed 20% cut in BBC income would only result from the BBC voluntarily deciding not to collect licence fees from the over-75s.</p> <p><strong>David Elstein</strong><br />London SW15<br /></p> <h2><strong>The errors of English rugby</strong></h2> <p>A conclusion that the review of England’s Rugby World Cup campaign (“<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/oct/31/new-zealand-australia-rugby-world-cup-final-match-report\" title=\"\">Irresistible All Blacks take proud place in history</a>”, Sport,) almost certainly won’t reach is the major difference in philosophy between the England and New Zealand rugby administrations.</p> <p>The All Blacks believe in long-term investment in players, thus instilling in the player confidence he has a long-term future with the team, versus a belief that only through competition could the best England team be forged.</p> <p>This led to many changes in key positions, particularly in the backs, and lack of confidence by the players that they had a long-term future.</p> <p><strong>David Murray</strong><br />Wallington, Surrey<br /></p> <h2><strong>End this roll reversal</strong></h2> <p>The news that the Wodehouse Society has banned bread roll throwing after red wine was spilt at the Houston convention (“<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/oct/31/americans-celebrate-pg-wodehouse-in-seattle\" title=\"\">I say, Jeeves, we’re bally masters of jollity for these American chappies</a>”, In Focus) marks a sad decline in the mainly British tradition of mixing literary and cultural discussion with throwing food and drink.</p> <p>In his youth, Hilaire Belloc attended parties where discussion was enlivened by throwing port, so much so that a special brand of “throwing port” was provided for the purpose.</p> <p><strong>DBC Reed</strong><br />Northampton<br /></p>","internalOctopusCode":"10954392","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-08T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2402718","internalContentCode":"458347361","internalRevision":"55","publication":"The Observer","trailText":"There are limits to what the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority can do","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Egg freezing is developing but more knowledge is needed","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"false","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-08T00:04:01.926Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/6e514edc1a3c673fbadd0edcc69c5d6d393c51c2/0_265_4668_2799/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"563ca20ae4b0fd5772b4d826","newspaperPageNumber":"40","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-11T00:04:02Z","standfirst":"There are limits to what the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority can do","linkText":"Egg freezing is developing but more knowledge is needed | Letters","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2015-11-08T00:04:02.118Z","legallySensitive":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/th